    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {5\mathopen{}\left(n+4\right)-7\mathopen{}\left(n-7\right)}={69}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\{0\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
5(n +4) -7(n-7)       \amp = 69 \\
5(n +4) +(-7)(n+(-7)) \amp = 69 \\
5n +5 \cdot 4 +(-7) \cdot n +(-7) \cdot (-7) \amp = 69 \\
5n +20 -7n +49 \amp = 69 \\
5n -7n +20+49 \amp = 69 \\
      -2n +69 \amp = 69 \\
      -2n +69\mathbf{{}-69} \amp = 69\mathbf{{}-69} \\
      -2n             \amp = 0 \\
      \frac{-2n}{-2} \amp = \frac{0}{-2} \\
      n                      \amp = 0
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The solution to this equation is <m>0</m>. To stress that this is a value assigned to <m>n</m>, some report <m>n = 0</m>. We can also say that the solution set is <m>\{0\}</m>, or that <m>n\in\left\{0\right\}</m>. If we substitute <m>0</m> in for <m>n</m> in the original equation <m>5\mathopen{}\left(n+4\right)-7\mathopen{}\left(n-7\right)=69</m>, the equation will be true. Please check this on your own; it is an important habit.</p>
</solution>
